sentences: Roscoe Mitchell (born August 3, 1940) is an American composer, jazz instrumentalist, and educator, known for being "a technically superb – if idiosyncratic – saxophonist".
The Penguin Guide to Jazz described him as "one of the key figures" in avant-garde jazz; All About Jazz stated in 2004 that he had been "at the forefront of modern music" for more than 35 years.
The Penguin Guide to Jazz described him as "one of the key figures" in avant-garde jazz; All About Jazz stated in 2004 that he had been "at the forefront of modern music" for more than 35 years.

In the 1950s, he joined the United States Army, during which time he was stationed in Heidelberg, Germany and played in military parades with fellow saxophonists Albert Ayler and Rubin Cooper, the latter of whom, Mitchell commented, "took me under his wing and taught me a lot of stuff".
section: == History == | === Early life ===

sentences: Mitchell returned to the United States in the early 1960s, relocated to the Chicago area, and performed in a band with Wilson Junior College undergraduates Malachi Favors (bass), Joseph Jarman, Henry Threadgill, and Anthony Braxton (all saxophonists).
section: == History == | === Early life ===

sentences: Mitchell also studied with Muhal Richard Abrams and played in his band, the Muhal Richard Abrams' Experimental Band, starting in 1961.
section: == History == | === Early life ===

sentences: In 1965, Mitchell was one of the first members of the non-profit organization Association for the Advancement of Creative Musicians (AACM), along with Jodie Christian (piano), Steve McCall (drums), and Phil Cohran (composer).
section: == History == | === AACM and the Art Ensemble of Chicago ===

sentences: The following year Mitchell, Lester Bowie (trumpet), Kalaparusha Maurice McIntyre (tenor saxophone), Favors, Lester Lashley (trombone), and Alvin Fielder (drums), recorded their first studio album, Sound.
section: == History == | === AACM and the Art Ensemble of Chicago ===

sentences: From 1967 Mitchell, Bowie, Favors and, on occasion, Jarman performed as the Roscoe Mitchell Art Ensemble, then the Art Ensemble, and finally in 1969 were billed as the Art Ensemble of Chicago.
section: == History == | === AACM and the Art Ensemble of Chicago ===

sentences: From 1967 Mitchell, Bowie, Favors and, on occasion, Jarman performed as the Roscoe Mitchell Art Ensemble, then the Art Ensemble, and finally in 1969 were billed as the Art Ensemble of Chicago.
section: == History == | === AACM and the Art Ensemble of Chicago ===

sentences: The group lived and performed in Europe from 1969 to 1971, though they arrived without any percussionist after Wilson left.
section: == History == | === AACM and the Art Ensemble of Chicago ===

sentences: The Art Ensemble of Chicago have been described as becoming "possibly the most highly acclaimed jazz band" in the 1970s and 1980s.
section: == History == | === AACM and the Art Ensemble of Chicago ===

sentences: Mitchell and the others returned to the States in 1971.
section: == History == | === Creative Arts Collective and beyond ===

sentences: After having been back in Chicago for three years, Mitchell then established the Creative Arts Collective (CAC) in 1974 that had a similar musical aesthetic to the AACM.
section: == History == | === Creative Arts Collective and beyond ===

sentences: After having been back in Chicago for three years, Mitchell then established the Creative Arts Collective (CAC) in 1974 that had a similar musical aesthetic to the AACM.
section: == History == | === Creative Arts Collective and beyond ===

sentences: Mitchell also formed the Sound Ensemble in the early 1970s, an "outgrowth of the CAC" in his words, that consisted mainly of Mitchell, Hugh Ragin, Jaribu Shahid, Tani Tabbal, and Spencer Barefield.
section: == History == | === Creative Arts Collective and beyond ===

sentences: In the 1990s, Mitchell started to experiment in classical music with such composers/artists such as Pauline Oliveros, Thomas Buckner, and Borah Bergman, the latter two of which formed a trio with Mitchell called Trio Space.
section: == History == | === Creative Arts Collective and beyond ===

sentences: Buckner was also part of another group with Mitchell and Gerald Oshita called Space in the late 1990s.
section: == History == | === Creative Arts Collective and beyond ===

sentences: He then conceived the Note Factory in 1992 with various old and new collaborators as another evolution of the Sound Ensemble.
section: == History == | === Creative Arts Collective and beyond ===

sentences: In 1999, the band was hit hard with the death of Bowie, but Mitchell fought off the urge to recast his position in the group, stating simply "You can't do that" in an interview with Allaboutjazz.com editor-in-chief Fred Jung.
section: == History == | === Creative Arts Collective and beyond ===

sentences: In 2007, Mitchell was named Darius Milhaud Chair of Composition at Mills College in Oakland, California, where he currently lives.
section: == History == | === Creative Arts Collective and beyond ===

section: == History == | === Creative Arts Collective and beyond ===

sentences: Mitchell was chosen by Jeff Mangum of Neutral Milk Hotel to perform at the All Tomorrow's Parties festival in March 2012 in Minehead, England.
